T1  - Does diversification destroy value? Evidence from the industry shocks
AU  - Lamont, Owen A.
AU  - Polk, Christopher
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 63
IS  - 1
SP  - 51
EP  - 77
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/01/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-405X(01)00089-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304405X01000897
KW  - Diversified firms
KW  - Internal capital markets
AB  - Does corporate diversification reduce shareholder value? Since firms endogenously choose to diversify, exogenous variation in diversification is necessary to draw inferences about the causal effect. We examine changes in the within-firm dispersion of industry investment, or “diversity”. We find that exogenous changes in diversity, due to changes in industry investment, are negatively related to firm value. Thus diversification destroys value, consistent with the inefficient internal capital markets hypothesis. Measurement error does not cause this finding. We also find that exogenous changes in industry cash flow diversity are negatively related to firm value.
